        "id": 6324,
        "name": "Markus Pilman",
        "username": "markus.pilman",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/markus.pilman/{size}/379_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-02-26T23:24:16.672Z",
        "cooked": "<p>git submodules are super painful in my experience, so I am kind of opposed using this.</p>\n<p>An additional option would be using a package manager (for example <a href=\"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/vcpkg?view=vs-2019\">vcpkg</a> or <a href=\"https://conan.io\">conan</a>).</p>\n<p>I evaluated conan quite a while ago and it was painful and created more problems than it solved. We could evaluate package managers again, maybe there is something that we like.</p>\n<p>Of all solutions currently available I like the cmake solution best (find dependency on the system and use that or use <code>ExternalProject_add</code> if it was not found). The main drawback is that it involves some work adding a dependency. But imho this is a feature, if adding dependencies is super easy, we will soon build against every C++ library out there (and become Java <img src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/wink.png?v=9\" title=\":wink:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":wink:\"> )</p>",
